Under low temperature conditions $k T \ll \varepsilon$, we can discuss using thermodynamics and statistical mechanics theories, respectively.

1. Thermodynamic Theory:

The temperature $T$ relates to entropy $S$, internal energy $U$, and volume $V$ as follows:

\begin{equation*}
\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial U}\right)_{V}=\frac{1}{T} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

Since $U=n \varepsilon$, we can rewrite equation (7) as:

\begin{equation*}
\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial n}\right)_{V}=\frac{\varepsilon}{T} \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

Using equations (4) and (8), we can obtain the fraction of occupied interstitial positions as:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{n}{N}=8 \exp \left(-\frac{\varepsilon}{k T}\right) \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

2. Statistical Mechanics Theory:

The probability $P$ of a system being in a state with energy $E$ and degeneracy $g$ is given by:

\begin{equation*}
P=\frac{g \exp (-\beta E)}{Z} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

where $\beta=1 / k T$, $E=n \varepsilon$, and $Z$ is the partition function of the system (a constant). In case (1), the probability of the system being in a state with $n$ excited atoms is

\begin{equation*}
P(n) \propto 8^{n} \cdot\binom{N}{n} \cdot \exp (-\beta n \varepsilon) \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

This probability reaches a maximum at a specific value $ \bar{n} $ of $n$, which can be determined by:

\begin{equation*}
\left(\frac{\partial \ln P(n)}{\partial n}\right)_{n=\bar{n}}=0 \tag{13}
\end{equation*}

Substituting equation (12) into equation (13), we again obtain equation (9).

