problem:
An ideal Fermi gas consists of particles with a total number $N$, a volume $V$, and an energy $E$. The state vector of the particles is denoted as $|i, j, s\rangle$, where $i$ and $j$ are orbital quantum numbers, and $s$ is the spin quantum number, which can take the values $1/2$ and $-1/2$. The energy level $\varepsilon_{i}$ of the particles depends only on the quantum number $i$, thus it is degenerate with a degeneracy of $g_{i}$. Assume that at most one particle can occupy each quantum state, and two quantum states $|i, j, 1/2\rangle$ and $|i, j, -1/2\rangle$ with the same orbital quantum numbers $i$ and $j$ cannot be occupied simultaneously. Provide the expression for the number of particles $N_{i}$ occupying the energy level $\varepsilon_{i}$ in thermodynamic equilibrium. The equations for the total number of particles and the energy of the gas are given as follows:

The total number of particles in the gas is

\begin{equation*}
N=\sum_{i} N_{i} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The energy of the gas is

\begin{equation*}
E=\sum_{i} N_{i} \varepsilon_{i} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

solution:
Since for the same pair of $i$ and $j$, the spin can have two different orientations, and the quantum states $|i, j, 1/2\rangle$ and $|i, j, -1/2\rangle$ cannot be simultaneously occupied, the number of microstates for the gas given a set $\left\{\varepsilon_{i}, g_{i}, N_{i}\right\}$ is

\begin{equation*}
w=\prod_{i}\left[\frac{\left(g_{i}/2\right)!}{N_{i}!\left(g_{i}/2-N_{i}\right)!} 2^{N_{i}}\right] \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

According to the principle of equal probabilities or the principle of maximum likelihood, the equation determining the most probable distribution or equilibrium distribution is

\begin{equation*}
-\frac{\partial}{\partial N_{i}}\left[\ln w+\alpha\left(N-\sum_{i} N_{i}\right)+\beta\left(E-\sum_{i} N_{i} \varepsilon_{i}\right)\right]=0 \tag{4}
\end{equation*}

Here, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are two Lagrange multipliers. Finally, assuming $N_{i} \gg 1, g_{i}/2-N_{i} \gg 1$, by using the Stirling approximation, from equations (3) and (4) we can obtain

\begin{equation*}
N_{i}=\frac{g_{i}}{\exp \left(\alpha+\beta \varepsilon_{i}\right)+2} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

where $\alpha=-\beta \mu, \beta=1/(k T), T$ and $\mu$ are the temperature and chemical potential of the gas respectively, and $k$ is the Boltzmann constant.

The internal energy $U$ of a non-relativistic ideal gas is $U=3 p V / 2$. From the pressure equation, the internal energy of the weakly degenerate Bose gas can be expressed as

\begin{equation*}
U=\frac{3}{2} N k T\left(1-0.1768 y-3.300 \times 10^{-3} y^{2}\right) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

